Date: 1/12/1957
Source: Personal Communication
Author: W.J. JIMPSON
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: [Words heard in N.Z. but not Britain] `Shift'; the equivalent is `move' or, in the words of the professional carrier, `to remove.' We [British] never shift from one house to another, though a student may `shift his quarters'
Notes: (Tolaga Bay)

Date: 3/12/1957
Source: Letter
Author: MARJORIE E. ALCOCK
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote:  I list below the words I can think of [as having different meanings in Britian and NZ.]: <i>N.Z</i>. shift: <i>English</i> Move house, or Remove. `Shift' is used colloquially for moving small objects, or oneself, i.e. `shift up.'
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1982
Source: Sea Change
Author: GILDERDALE
Vol / Page: 241
Edition:
Quote: <i>shift</i> Move house. Noted in I.M. Peacocke's <i>When I Was Seven </i>(1927) page 175: `We `moved', the children nex door called it `shifting', ut we were instructed that while it was permissible to say `moving' only the vulgar said `shifting'
